Malaysia Stocks: AirAsia, Ecofirst, Malaysian Air, Perwaja

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-08-01T09:13:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-01/malaysia-stocks-aic-autov-jotech-malaysian-airline-perwaja.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. local-time close in
Kuala Lumpur.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 9.2 points, or 0.6
percent, to 1,558.01, snapping a three-day decline.        AirAsia Bhd. (AIRA)  ,  Asia ’s biggest budget carrier, rose
1.5 percent to 3.99 ringgit, a record close, after UOB-Kay Hian
Holdings Ltd. raised its share estimate to 4.60 ringgit from
3.70 ringgit. The stock was maintained at “buy,” UOB-Kay Hian
wrote in a report today.  Ecofirst Consolidated Bhd. (ECOF)  , an oil-palm planter
and timber group, advanced 3.3 percent to 15.5 sen, the biggest
increase since July 22. Ecofirst had a profit of 4.2 million
ringgit ($1.4 million) in the fourth quarter ended May 31,
compared with a net loss of 21.9 million ringgit a year earlier,
according to a company statement.        Malaysian Airline System Bhd. (MAS)  , the national
carrier, advanced 2.7 percent to 1.52 ringgit, the highest since
July 7. The airline named Md. Nor Yusof as chairman after
Mohamed Munir Abdul Majid quit the company, it said in a
statement. Md. Nor is chairman of CIMB Group Holdings Bhd.        Perwaja Holdings Bhd. (PERH)  , a steelmaker, jumped 12
percent to 1.14 ringgit, the most since May 8, 2009. OSK
Research Sdn. upgraded the stock to “buy” from “trading buy”
after state news agency Bernama reported that the company is
close to securing an iron-ore mining permit in Terengganu state.  To contact the reporter on this story:
